### How did you do?

A, B and D each each been accused by two people. Very suspicious! They are our top candidates.

Looking more closely, B, C and D accuse two people each. However A only accuses B.

Let's say that each person can give out one accusation point, worth a score of 1.

If a person accuses just one other, they give all of their accusation score to that person.

If they accuses two people, each of the accused will receive half an accusation point.

So A has given their entire accusation point to B whilst D has also given half an accusation point to B.

We can say B has 1.5 accusation points, where as A and D only have 1. Making B our traitor!

## Quality links

From now on we'll stop thinking about traitors and think about websites instead. Instead of accusing each other, the websites will link to each other.

The algorithm assumes that the more important a website is, the more likely it is to receive links from other websites.

But there is a problem with assuming that the page with the most incoming links is automatically the most important.

It's possible to game the system. A nefarious person could simply create hundreds of other websites, all linking to their main site just to make that site appear to be more important.


### Pick the most popular website

Let's take another look at our diagram and say than B now also links to A.

Can you click on the websites so that they are added to the box in order of importance, that is order of their PageRank score?

Once again you can click on a circle to add them to the box, then click on them again if you'd like to remove them. Click on the click on the ‘check answer’ button once you've made your selection.

