### How did you do?

This might have been slightly tricky. Congratulations if you got it in one and no worries if you're still figuring it out.

Site A now has three incoming links, more than any other site, and yet site B is still ranked in first place. Why is that?

To stop websites gaming the system, not all links are treated equally. The algorithm assigns more weight to links coming from websites that already have a high PageRank score. It's not just about the number of links, it's about the quality or 'weight' of those links.

<!-- In other words, a page becomes more 'important', the more it is linked to by 'important' pages. -->

If a big, respected site like the _BBC_ or the _New York Times_ links to you, that will mean much more to your PageRank score than a link from my personal blog about ginger cats.

Because site A is a high ranking site, its link to site B is enough to push B to the top spot even though B technically has less incoming links.

## How does PageRank decide who is best

PageRank uses a technique called the a Random Surfer. This is more than just an erratic water sports enthusiast. The Random Surfer is a computer programme that acts like an internet user who has decided to surf the web by randomly clicking on links. 

